From: Namecoin Integration <namecoin-integration@example.com>
Date: 2026-04-16
Subject: [PATCH 4/4] netwerk/dns: Hook nsNamecoinResolver into nsHostResolver

Modifies nsHostResolver::ResolveHost() to route .bit TLD queries to
nsNamecoinResolver when network.namecoin.enabled is true.

The hook is a minimal, surgical change:
  1. After the host record is locked but before system DNS is attempted,
     check if TLD == "bit" and namecoin resolver is enabled.
  2. If yes, dispatch to nsNamecoinResolver::Resolve() instead.
  3. nsNamecoinResolver callback populates the nsHostRecord with NetAddr
     results, exactly as the existing DNS path does.
  4. If the resolver is disabled or the name is not .bit, fall through to
     normal DNS resolution (no behavioral change).

nsNamecoinResolver is held as a static singleton on nsHostResolver,
initialized lazily on first .bit query.

Error handling:
  - If all ElectrumX servers fail: DNS query fails with NS_ERROR_NET_INTERRUPT
    (not a silent NXDOMAIN — .bit is not a real TLD)
  - If name is expired: NS_ERROR_FAILURE with specific error message
  - If name not found: NS_ERROR_FAILURE

Thread safety:
  - nsNamecoinResolver uses a Mutex for server list access
  - ResolveInternal() always runs on background thread (asserts this)
  - Callback fires on main thread via NS_DispatchToMainThread

Bug: <to be filed on bugzilla.mozilla.org>
Reviewed-by: <pending>

